retrieval info.text: Edward Davis Wood Jr. (October 10, 1924 – December 10, 1978) was an American filmmaker, actor, and pulp novelist. He directed several low-budget science fiction, crime and horror films in the 1950s that later became cult classics, including 'Glen or Glenda', 'Jail Bait', 'Bride of the Monster', 'Plan 9 from Outer Space' and 'Night of the Ghouls'. In the 1960s and 1970s, he moved towards sexploitation and pornographic films such as 'The Sinister Urge', 'Orgy of the Dead' and 'Necromania'. Wood's films are notable for their campy aesthetics, technical errors, and eccentric casts. He was posthumously awarded a Golden Turkey Award for Worst Director of All Time in 1980. A biopic of his life, 'Ed Wood' (1994), was directed by Tim Burton and starred Johnny Depp as Wood. The film received critical acclaim and various awards, including two Academy Awards.
retrieval info.infobox: Edward Davis Wood Jr., commonly known as Ed Wood, was born on October 10, 1924 in Poughkeepsie, New York, U.S., and died on December 10, 1978 in Los Angeles, California, U.S. He was a filmmaker, author, and actor active from 1947 to 1978. He also served in the United States Marine Corps from 1942 to 1944, participating in the World War II Gilbert and Marshall Islands campaign. He was married twice and had one daughter.

"Kiss and Tell" is a 1945 American comedy film starring Shirley Temple as Corliss Archer. The plot revolves around two teenage girls causing concern for their parents as they start showing interest in boys. The movie is based on a Broadway play of the same name, and the Corliss Archer short stories, all written by F. Hugh Herbert. A sequel film, "A Kiss for Corliss," was released in 1949.
retrieval info.infobox: The 1945 film 'Kiss and Tell' was directed by Richard Wallace, written by F. Hugh Herbert from his own play, and produced by Sol C. Siegel. It starred Shirley Temple, Jerome Courtland, Walter Abel, and Katharine Alexander. The cinematography was handled by Charles Lawton Jr. and edited by Charles Nelson. The music was composed by Werner R. Heymann. The film was distributed by Columbia Pictures and was released on October 4, 1945. It has a running time of 90 minutes. The film was made in the United States and is in English. At the box office, it earned $1.2 million.

retrieval info.text: Shirley Temple Black (born Shirley Jane Temple) was an American actress, singer, dancer, and diplomat, who was Hollywood's number-one box-office draw as a child actress from 1934 to 1938. She later served as the United States Ambassador to Ghana and Czechoslovakia, and also as Chief of Protocol of the United States. Her film career began in 1931 and she became famous for her performance in 'Bright Eyes' released in 1934. Her diplomatic career began in 1969. In 1988, she published her autobiography, Child Star. She is 18th on the American Film Institute's list of the greatest female American screen legends of classic Hollywood cinema.
retrieval info.infobox: Shirley Jane Temple was born on April 23, 1928 in Santa Monica, California, U.S. and died on February 10, 2014 in Woodside, California, U.S. She was an actress, singer, dancer, and diplomat.
